      "title": "Doppler's Effect",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Doppler's Effect</strong></h3><p>When a sound source and an observer are in relative motion with respect to the medium in which the waves propagate, the frequency of waves observed is different from the frequency of sound emitted by the source. This phenomenon is called Doppler effect. This is due to the wave-nature of sound propagation and is therefore applicable to light waves also. The apparent change of colour of a star can be explained by this principle.</p><p><strong>Calculation of Apparent Frequency&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Suppose $\\text{v}$ is the velocity of sound in air, ${{\\text{v}}_{0}}$ is the velocity of the observer $\\left( \\text{O} \\right)$ and $\\text{f}$ is the frequency of the source.</p><p><strong>(i) Source moves towards stationary observer </strong>: If the source $\\text{S}$ were stationary the $\\text{f}$ waves sent out in one second towards the observer $\\text{O}$ would occupy a distance $\\text{v}$, and the wavelength would be v/f.</p><p>If $\\text{S}$ moves with a velocity ${{\\text{v}}_{\\text{S}}}$ towards $\\text{O}$, the $\\text{f}$ waves sent out occupy a distance $\\left( \\text{v}-{{\\text{v}}_{\\text{s}}} \\right)$ because $\\text{S}$ has moved a distance ${{\\text{v}}_{\\text{S}}}$ towards $\\text{O}$ in $1\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ s}$. So the apparent wavelength would be</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"249\" height=\"149\">&nbsp;</p><p>${\\lambda }'=\\left( \\frac{\\text{v}-{{\\text{v}}_{\\text{s}}}}{\\text{f}} \\right)$</p><p>Thus, apparent frequency</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; \\text{{f}'}=\\frac{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ velocity }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ of }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ sound }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ relative }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ to }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }O}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ wavelength }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ of }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ wave }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ reaching }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }O} \\\\ {} &amp; {} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>${f}'=\\frac{\\text{v}}{{{\\lambda }'}}=\\text{f}\\left( \\frac{\\text{v}}{\\text{v}-{{\\text{v}}_{\\text{S}}}} \\right)$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" width=\"235\" height=\"158\">&nbsp;</p><p><strong>(ii) Source moves away from stationary observer: </strong>Now, apparent wavelength</p><p>${\\lambda }'=\\frac{\\text{v}+{{\\text{v}}_{\\text{S}}}}{\\text{f}}$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }$ Apparent frequency</p><p>${f}'$= v/ ${\\lambda }'$</p><p>or ${f}'=f\\left( \\frac{v}{v+{{v}_{s}}} \\right)$</p><p><strong>(iii) Observer, moves towards stationary source&nbsp;</strong></p><p>${f}'=\\frac{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ velocity }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ of }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ sound }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ relative }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ to }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }O}{\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ wavelength }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ of }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ wave }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ reaching }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }O}$</p><p>Here, velocity of sound relative to $\\text{O}=\\text{v}+{{\\text{v}}_{0}}$</p><p>and wavelength of waves reaching $\\text{O}=\\text{v}/\\text{f}$</p><p>$\\therefore \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ {f}'}=\\frac{\\text{v}+{{\\text{v}}_{0}}}{\\text{v}/\\text{f}}=\\text{f}\\left( \\frac{\\text{v}+{{\\text{v}}_{0}}}{\\text{v}} \\right)$</p><p><strong>(iv) Observer moves away from the stationary source&nbsp;</strong></p><p>$\\text{{f}'}=\\frac{\\text{v}-{{\\text{v}}_{0}}}{\\text{v}/\\text{f}}=\\text{f}\\left( \\frac{\\text{v}-{{\\text{v}}_{0}}}{\\text{v}} \\right)$</p><p><strong>(v) Source and observer both moves towards each other&nbsp;</strong></p><p>${f}'=\\frac{\\left( v+{{v}_{0}} \\right)}{\\left( \\frac{v-{{v}_{s}}}{f} \\right)}=f\\left( \\frac{v+{{v}_{0}}}{v-{{v}_{s}}} \\right)$</p><p><strong>(vi) Both moves away from each other&nbsp;</strong></p><p>${f}'=f\\left[ \\frac{v-{{v}_{0}}}{v+{{v}_{s}}} \\right]$</p><p><strong>(vii) Source moves towards observer but observer moves away from source&nbsp;</strong></p><p>${f}'=f\\left( \\frac{v-{{v}_{0}}}{v-{{v}_{S}}} \\right)$</p><p><strong>(viii) Source moves away from observer but observer moves towards source&nbsp;</strong></p><p>${f}'=f\\left[ \\frac{v+{{v}_{0}}}{v+{{v}_{s}}} \\right]$</p>",
      "position": 0,
